We played 10,000 on New Year‚Äôs Day, and we had a disagreement about if you have 2/5 scoring die whether to roll 3 or 4.
I‚Äôve literally never done probability math EVER‚Ä¶ but I felt that it was more effective to roll 4 than 3.
So I attempted to simulate rolls in #rstats!
Simulating 10,000 rolls
So we need to create a dataset of possible rolls, and how common these are when randomly created. We‚Äôll set a seed so that we can reproduce the code, and for puns sake we‚Äôll roll the dice 10,000 times to match our game‚Äôs title.
Importantly, we also will be breaking this down into 5x 10,000 samples which is: - Rolling 1 dice all the way to rolling 5 dice (max possible).
Generating this is fairly straightforward using tidyr::crossing() and purrr::map() + sample().
Crossing
tidyr::crossing() takes multiple vectors and creates a tibble of all the possible combinations. Thus we can use it to generate the number of dice in hand along with our 10,000 simulations per number of dice in hand. Our toy example below shows the expected behavior, and then we‚Äôll assign the rolls to a stored dataframe.


# Toy example
# 1 to 5 dice in hand x 5 trials/per dice group = 25 observations
crossing(
  dice_in_hand = seq(1, 5, 1),
  trial = 1:5
)


# A tibble: 25 x 2
